posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: Perfect. That tells me enough to say that something else is being told to use the same PWM port as your servo. Do you have other servos/PWM controllers in your code?

posts.name: Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: It turns out that there were two things both set to port 6.  Whenever I look at driverstation it shows that there is robot code.  When I press the button (x) that I set the servo command to, it shows that there’s no robot code for a second, disables the robot, then the robot code shows up again.  When I comment out anything referencing the servo, it works when I press the button.

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: Is this issue still happening after changing one or both away from port 6? If so look for error text again in the console.

posts.name: Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: I was able to get it working, except that the servo only moved once.  It moved when I first tested the code, but now it won’t work even though I didn’t change the code at all.  I know it works because I put a few System.out.println in the servo subsystem, servo command, and where the stop command is.  It shows the messages on the console, but it doesn’t actually move the servo.

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked: What are the values for Constants.SERVO_EXTEND and Constants.SERVO_STOP ?

posts.name: Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: SERVO_EXTEND is set to 0 (sorry the name is a bit misleading) and SERVO_STOP is set to 0.5

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: I’m beginning to suspect that it’s more of a wiring problem or a misconception of what the servo should be doing. Would you please explain a bit about what you expect the servo to do when it “works”?

posts.name: Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: Oh yeah, sorry for not doing that already.  It’s a servo that extends and retracts.  We have it blocking the intake of our shooter when it’s extended, and we’re trying to make it retract when we press the button.  We’re doing this so our shooter motors can get to full speed before the ball actually gets shot out.

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: How are you commanding the extend and retract methods? My guess is they’re conflicting.

posts.name: Alex Chadwick
Amicus1
Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: It was StopServo(); but I changed the name.  I’m not sure if it matters what the name is.  I think I was having the same problem even when it was called StopServo();

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: The name won’t matter as long as you’re consistent. What I’m also seeing is this command never ending (and thus extending) unless interrupted either by an “retract again” command or another event. Are you using whenPressed or whileHeld on the button for the command?

posts.name: Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: I’m using whileHeld.  Also, even if I changed the value of either constant, it wouldn’t move.

posts.name: Harris
Alex Chadwick
posts.cooked: Yeah, I forgot to say that I already changed that a while ago (probably somewhere around the 8th response in the thread) and it worked.  Thanks for the tip though!

posts.name: Amicus1
posts.cooked: Where does the servo get stuck, extended or retracted? That will tell us which operation is winning out for control of the servo.
